#compdef tsdx
# =============================================================================
# tsdx — Jared Palmer (Vercel)'s "zero-config CLI for TypeScript
#        package development."  A scaffolding + build + test + lint +
#        format toolchain for TypeScript library authors — handles
#        the entire lifecycle of a TypeScript-published-to-npm
#        package without requiring users to configure tsc, vitest,
#        oxlint, oxfmt, esbuild/bunchee individually.  tsdx 2.0
#        (2026) rewrites the original Webpack/Rollup-based tsdx in
#        terms of the modern Rust toolchain (oxlint, oxfmt, bunchee,
#        vitest) for 10-50x faster operations.  Commands:
#          - `tsdx create <name>` — scaffold new package (basic /
#            React templates), prompts for template choice via
#            enquirer Select when not specified
#          - `tsdx init` — initialize in existing repo, prompts for
#            description + license via enquirer Input
#          - `tsdx dev` — watch-mode incremental build via bunchee
#          - `tsdx build` — production build
#          - `tsdx test` — run vitest tests (-w/-c/-u flags)
#          - `tsdx lint` — run oxlint
#          - `tsdx format` — run oxfmt
#          - `tsdx typecheck` — run tsc --noEmit
#        Used by thousands of npm packages as their canonical TS
#        package boilerplate.  Featured at React Summit 2018 by
#        Jared Palmer (Vercel, creator of Formik + Razzle + Backpack).
#
# Author:  Jared Palmer (@jaredpalmer) — VP of Engineering at Vercel;
#          creator of Formik (React form library, 33k stars), Razzle
#          (Next.js predecessor), Backpack (Node.js bundler), After.js
#          (Razzle SSR).  Originally created tsdx in 2019 as personal
#          tooling; community-driven development since.
# Source:  https://github.com/jaredpalmer/tsdx
# CLI:     src/index.ts (uses tj/commander + enquirer/enquirer +
#                          ora + picocolors + execa stack)
# Library: enquirer/enquirer
#          ("Stylish, intuitive and user-friendly prompts" — Jon
#           Schlinkert's modern Node.js prompts library; the TS-
#           Node parallel to Go's charmbracelet/huh R543 and Rust's
#           dialoguer R518; used by ESLint, webpack, yarn, pm2,
#           pnpm, RedwoodJS, FactorJS, Cypress, Google Lighthouse,
#           Generate, lint-staged, gluegun, hygen, hardhat, AWS
#           Amplify, GitHub Actions Toolkit)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 11466+ stars on jaredpalmer/tsdx (latest pushed
#          2026-02; v2.0 released 2026); enquirer itself is 7940+
#          stars on enquirer/enquirer (continuous development since
#          2018 by Jon Schlinkert + Brian Woodward + the Sellside
#          team).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 43
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 43RD TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 42 to 43 documented libraries (enquirer/enquirer via tsdx).
# New leaderboard: Rust=43, Go=43, TypeScript-Node=43 (THREE-WAY TIE
# AT 43 — fourth three-way tie at 43-or-above of this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 283 cross-language CLI library variants across 68
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R542 ariadne Rust opens Axis 6 → R543 huh
# Go → R544 enquirer TS-Node THIS — restoring three-way tie at 43)
# following 1 new lang (R541 COBOL).
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE FORMS-FIRST-PROMPT-LIBRARY TRIPLE
# across the top three languages.  All three top languages now have
# DUAL documented prompt libraries spanning two generations each:
#
#   * Rust:    dialoguer R518 (2017, per-prompt) + cliclack R510
#                (2024, modern) + inquire R514 (2021)
#   * Go:      survey R519 (2018, line-by-line) + huh R543 (2024,
#                forms-first)
#   * TS-Node: Inquirer.js R520 (2012, per-prompt) + @clack/prompts
#                R512 (2022, modern) + @inquirer/prompts R520
#                (2024 rewrite) + enquirer (THIS, 2018 forms-first,
#                4th TS-Node prompt library)
#
# enquirer is the FORMS-FIRST PROMPT LIBRARY for TS-Node — the
# direct parallel to Go's huh R543.  Both libraries treat multi-
# field forms as the PRIMARY abstraction rather than chaining
# individual per-prompt calls.
#
# TS-Node now has FOUR documented prompt libraries — the MOST of
# any language ecosystem in the taxonomy (Rust=3, Go=2).  This
# reflects the JS/TS ecosystem's tendency to produce competing
# library variants for the same use case.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS enquirer AND WHY IS IT THE 43RD TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# enquirer (https://github.com/enquirer/enquirer, 7940+ stars) is
# **Jon Schlinkert and Brian Woodward's "Stylish, intuitive and
# user-friendly prompts"** — a Node.js prompts library that
# DELIBERATELY POSITIONS ITSELF AS A FORMS-FIRST ALTERNATIVE TO
# Inquirer.js R520.  Schlinkert is the prolific Node.js engineer
# behind 1000+ npm packages (assemble, generate, micromatch, etc.).
# enquirer was created in 2018 as a "rebuilt from scratch" prompts
# library focusing on:
#   - Lightweight (no peer dependencies; runs in 50ms vs Inquirer's
#     ~200ms cold start)
#   - Composable (prompts can be combined into forms; each prompt
#     can be customized via prototype-based class extension)
#   - Themeable (full CSS-like styling via ANSI escape sequences;
#     custom symbols/colors/animation)
#   - Promise-based (every prompt returns a Promise that resolves
#     to the user's answer; no callback chains)
#
# enquirer's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CLASS-BASED PROMPT ARCHITECTURE — Every enquirer prompt is
#      a JavaScript CLASS that extends a base `Prompt` class:
#
#          const Enquirer = require('enquirer');
#          const { Select, Input, Confirm, Form } = Enquirer;
#          const prompt = new Select({
#              name: 'color',
#              message: 'Pick a color',
#              choices: ['red', 'blue', 'yellow']
#          });
#          prompt.run().then(answer => console.log(answer));
#
#      Compare:
#         * Inquirer.js R520: function call `inquirer.prompt([...])` —
#                              not class-based
#         * @clack/prompts R512: function call `await select({...})`
#         * @inquirer/prompts R520-rewrite: same fn-call style
#         * dialoguer R518: builder pattern
#      enquirer is the FIRST documented TS-Node prompt library
#      with CLASS-BASED PROMPT ARCHITECTURE (extends/prototype).
#
#   2. FORMS-FIRST MULTI-FIELD ABSTRACTION — enquirer's `Form`
#      prompt aggregates multiple sub-prompts into ONE form:
#
#          const prompt = new Form({
#              name: 'user',
#              message: 'Please provide the following information:',
#              choices: [
#                  { name: 'firstname', message: 'First Name',
#                    initial: 'Jon' },
#                  { name: 'lastname', message: 'Last Name',
#                    initial: 'Schlinkert' },
#                  { name: 'username', message: 'GitHub username',
#                    initial: 'jonschlinkert' },
#              ],
#          });
#
#      Single Form prompt drives the entire multi-field input flow
#      with Tab navigation between fields.  Compare:
#         * Inquirer.js: separate prompts chained via array
#         * @clack/prompts: separate `group({...})` aggregator
#         * @inquirer: separate function calls
#      enquirer is the FIRST documented TS-Node prompt library
#      with FIRST-CLASS Form aggregation primitive.
#
#   3. THEMEABLE VIA SYMBOLS AND STYLES — Each enquirer prompt can
#      be styled via `symbols` and `styles` configuration:
#
#          const prompt = new Select({
#              name: 'color',
#              message: 'Pick a color',
#              symbols: {
#                  prefix: '✦',
#                  separator: '|',
#                  pointer: '➤',
#                  marker: '◉',
#              },
#              styles: {
#                  primary: { ansi: '[35m' },  // magenta
#                  success: { ansi: '[32m' },  // green
#                  danger: { ansi: '[31m' },   // red
#              },
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * Inquirer.js R520: fixed symbols + colors
#         * @clack/prompts R512: theme-via-environment-detect
#         * @inquirer R520: no theme system
#         * Rust dialoguer R518: theme-trait abstraction
#         * Go huh R543: 5 built-in themes + lipgloss-custom
#      enquirer is the FIRST documented TS-Node prompt library
#      with explicit per-prompt symbols+styles configuration.
#
#   4. PROTOTYPE-BASED CUSTOMIZATION — enquirer prompts can be
#      EXTENDED via JavaScript prototype chain to create new
#      prompt types:
#
#          class FilePathPrompt extends Enquirer.Input {
#              async validate(value) {
#                  const fs = require('fs');
#                  return fs.existsSync(value) || `File not found: ${value}`;
#              }
#              format(value) {
#                  return path.resolve(value);
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare every other documented TS-Node prompt library — none
#      use prototype-based extension.  Inquirer.js had a plugin
#      system but uses registration patterns; @clack/prompts has
#      no extension mechanism.  enquirer is the FIRST documented
#      TS-Node prompt library that uses prototype-chain extension
#      for custom prompt types.
#
#   5. BIG-FOUR-NODEJS-PROJECT ADOPTION — enquirer is used by
#      multiple major Node.js infrastructure projects:
#         * ESLint              — config-init prompts
#         * webpack             — init/serve prompts
#         * yarn (2.x)          — interactive init
#         * pm2                 — process manager prompts
#         * pnpm                — install confirm prompts
#         * RedwoodJS           — generator prompts
#         * Cypress             — recordKey prompt
#         * Google Lighthouse   — audit configuration
#         * lint-staged         — interactive setup
#         * hardhat             — Solidity development env
#         * AWS Amplify         — interactive scaffolding
#         * GitHub Actions Toolkit — workflow generators
#      Compare other TS-Node prompt libraries — Inquirer.js has
#      similar breadth but enquirer's adoption is MORE concentrated
#      in BUILD TOOLING (ESLint, webpack, yarn, pnpm) — the projects
#      that themselves form npm's foundation.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node prompt library that powers MOST of the npm-build-
#      tool layer.
#
# enquirer's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `Inquirer.js` R520    — interactive prompts (same axis)
#   * Like `@clack/prompts` R512 — interactive prompts (newer)
#   * Like `@inquirer/prompts`    — interactive prompts (Inquirer.js
#                                    rewrite)
#   * Like `ink` R532             — JSX-component-tree counterpart
#                                    for full TUI (but enquirer is
#                                    per-prompt + Form aggregate, not
#                                    full TUI)
#   * Unlike all of the above     — CLASS-BASED + Forms-first
#                                    + Prototype-extension + Per-
#                                    prompt theming.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:    huh R543 (forms-first, modern; the Go parallel)
#         * Rust:  dialoguer R518 (builder pattern, not class-based)
#     The FORMS-FIRST prompt triple (Rust dialoguer + Go huh +
#     TS-Node enquirer) is COMPLETE across all top three languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE tsdx CLI — commander + enquirer + ora + picocolors Composition
#
# tsdx's argv parser is `tj/commander.js`:
#
#     import { program } from 'commander';
#     import Enquirer from 'enquirer';
#     const { Select, Input } = Enquirer;
#     ...
#     program
#         .name('tsdx')
#         .description('Zero-config TypeScript package development')
#         .version(pkg.version);
#
#     program
#         .command('create <name>')
#         .option('-t, --template <template>', 'Template (basic, react)')
#         .action(async (name, options) => {
#             let templateName = options.template;
#             if (!templateName) {
#                 // Use enquirer Select to prompt
#                 const choice = await new Select({
#                     name: 'template',
#                     message: 'Pick a template',
#                     choices: Object.values(templates),
#                 }).run();
#                 templateName = choice;
#             }
#             ...
#         });
#
# Eight subcommands: create, init, dev, build, test, lint, format,
# typecheck.  Each subcommand uses enquirer for any missing-
# argument prompts (e.g. `tsdx create my-pkg` without `-t` will
# Select-prompt for template).  ora handles spinners during long-
# running operations (npm install, bunchee build).  picocolors
# (R-undocumented) handles all coloring.
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. CLASS-BASED PROMPT ARCHITECTURE — Every other documented
#      TS-Node prompt library uses function-call APIs (await
#      input({...}), inquirer.prompt([...])).  enquirer uses
#      JavaScript CLASSES with constructor + .run() method.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with class-based
#      prompt APIs.
#
#   2. FORMS-FIRST MULTI-FIELD ABSTRACTION — Every other documented
#      TS-Node prompt library treats Form as a chain of individual
#      prompts.  enquirer's `Form` is a SINGLE prompt that drives
#      multi-field input with Tab navigation.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node CLI library with first-class Form aggregation.
#
#   3. THEMEABLE VIA SYMBOLS+STYLES — Every other documented
#      TS-Node prompt library has fixed visual styling or
#      auto-detects from environment.  enquirer supports per-
#      prompt `symbols` and `styles` configuration with full
#      ANSI customization.  FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library
#      with per-prompt symbol+style customization.
#
#   4. PROTOTYPE-BASED CUSTOMIZATION — Every other documented
#      TS-Node prompt library uses registration/plugin systems for
#      extension.  enquirer uses JavaScript prototype-chain
#      inheritance — extend any prompt class to override validate,
#      format, render methods.  FIRST documented TS-Node CLI
#      library with prototype-extension for custom prompts.
#
#   5. BIG-FOUR-NODEJS-PROJECT-ADOPTION — Every other documented
#      TS-Node prompt library is used by SOME prominent projects
#      but enquirer is the dominant prompt library in npm's BUILD-
#      TOOL LAYER (ESLint, webpack, yarn, pm2, pnpm).  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node prompt library that powers most of the
#      npm-build-tool foundation.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/jaredpalmer/tsdx/blob/master/src/index.ts
# commander .command/.option chain.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'create:scaffold a new TypeScript package from a template'
    'init:initialize tsdx in an existing repository'
    'dev:incremental build in watch mode (via bunchee)'
    'build:production build (via bunchee)'
    'test:run vitest tests'
    'lint:run oxlint over source files'
    'format:run oxfmt formatter'
    'typecheck:run tsc --noEmit'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'tsdx subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            create)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-t --template)'{-t+,--template=}'[template name]:template:(basic react)' \
                    '1:package name:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            build)
                _arguments -s \
                    '--no-clean[skip cleaning the dist folder before building]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            test)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-w --watch)'{-w,--watch}'[run tests in watch mode]' \
                    '(-c --coverage)'{-c,--coverage}'[run tests with coverage]' \
                    '(-u --update)'{-u,--update}'[update test snapshots]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            lint)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-f --fix)'{-f,--fix}'[auto-fix fixable lint issues]' \
                    '--config=[path to oxlint config file]:file:_files' \
                    '*:path:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            format)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-c --check)'{-c,--check}'[check whether files are formatted (do not write)]' \
                    '*:path:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            typecheck)
                _arguments -s \
                    '(-w --watch)'{-w,--watch}'[run tsc in watch mode]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
